sequence.notes: Formation of a 2-substituted 1,3-dithiane via nucleophilic attack of lithiated dithiane on a bromoacetal.

sequence.reaction_type: Dithiane Alkylation / Nucleophilic Addition to Aldehyde
sequence.notes: Deprotonation of the dithiane at C2 followed by addition to a TBS-protected propanal, yielding a new C-C bond and a secondary alcohol.
Alkylation of a secondary alcohol with an allylic bromide using potassium hydride as base to form an alkenyl ether.
Deprotection of a TBS ether to a primary alcohol.
Oxidation of a primary alcohol to an aldehyde using Swern oxidation conditions.
Aldehyde undergoes Horner-Wadsworth-Emmons olefination with diethyl (gamma-butyrolacton-2-yl)phosphonate to form a Z-alkene.
Conversion of a lactone carbonyl to an exocyclic methylene group.
Diels-Alder reaction forms a complex polycyclic product with new stereocenters. Dithiane ring size correction, silane group correction, and multiple stereochemistry corrections were required.
Acid-catalyzed hydrolysis of dimethyl acetal and subsequent intramolecular cyclization/rearrangement of the furan moiety, forming an internal ether bridge and two hydroxyl groups.

Two hydroxyl groups are acylated to pivalate esters, while one bridgehead hydroxyl is oxidized to a ketone, accompanied by the cleavage of the adjacent cyclic ether and formation of a pivalate ester on the former ether methylene.
Stereoselective reduction of a ketone to a secondary alcohol using sodium borohydride, forming the 'up' hydroxyl stereoisomer.
Oxidation of 1,3-dithiane to a ketone using methyl iodide (MeI) as the electrophile and acetonitrile as solvent.
Base-catalyzed elimination of a pivalate group to form an alpha,beta-unsaturated ketone.
Conversion of phenyl-dimethylsilyl group to hydroxyl group.
Acetal formation from a vicinal diol and benzaldehyde, forming a 1,3-dioxane ring.
Stereoselective reduction of an α,β-unsaturated ketone to a secondary allylic alcohol using L-Selectride.
Conversion of a secondary alcohol to a TBS silyl ether.
Hydrolysis of methyl ester and pivalate to carboxylic acid and alcohol respectively.
Methylation of a carboxylic acid to its methyl ester using diazomethane.
Oxidation of a primary alcohol to an aldehyde using Dess-Martin periodinane.
Silylation of an aldehyde to form an E-configured enol silyl ether using TBSOTf and Et3N.

Ozonolysis of an exocyclic vinyl ether to an aldehyde. The input SMILES for both reactant and product contain a significant topological error: one of the OTBS groups is shown attached to a vinylic carbon (`O[C@H]1C=C`), whereas in the screenshot, it is attached to a saturated chiral carbon adjacent to a CH2 and then an internal double bond. This fundamental connectivity mismatch could not be corrected without completely regenerating the SMILES, which goes beyond simple 'correction' of the provided string.

Aldehyde functional group (CHO) is reduced to a primary alcohol (CH2OH). The provided SMILES for both reactant and product do not fully match the complex core structure shown in the screenshot. Notably, the phenyl group (Ph) and the methine carbon it is attached to in the dioxolane ring are missing from the SMILES strings. This represents a significant structural discrepancy, as these groups contribute 7 heavy atoms (6C from Ph + 1C from CH). The calculated heavy atom count for the provided SMILES (33 atoms, excluding junk) also differs from the expected formula C25H36O8Si (34 heavy atoms) for the complete molecule in the image. Therefore, the core connectivity represented by the SMILES is likely fundamentally different from the image.
Primary alcohol is converted to a tosylate.
(3 Steps)
Deprotection of a TBS ether to an alcohol using TBAF.
Oxidation of a secondary alcohol to a ketone using PDC.
Intramolecular cyclization and rearrangement of an acyl cyanide ester, promoted by DBU, leading to the formation of a 5-membered lactone ring and saturation of an alpha-beta unsaturated ketone.

Decyanation of the nitrile group to a ketone and oxidative cleavage of the lactone ring to an additional ketone. The symbol X o-o is interpreted as a peroxide-mediated reaction, and the reagent SMILES CC1(C)OO1 (dimethyldioxirane) is a plausible specific peroxide.
Methanolysis of the cyclic anhydride moiety, followed by intramolecular cyclization to form a new cyclic ether, a carboxylic acid, and a tertiary alcohol.
Methylation of a carboxylic acid to a methyl ester using diazomethane.
Benzylation of a tertiary alcohol using benzyl bromide and silver oxide.
Ketone is converted to an enol silyl ether using TBDMSOTf and triethylamine. All other functional groups and stereocenters are retained.
Addition of methyleneiminium salt to an enone (likely formed from silyl enol ether), leading to ketone formation and a quaternary ammonium side chain.
Hofmann-like elimination of a quaternary ammonium salt to form an exocyclic alkene.
Hydrogenation of the exocyclic alkene to a methyl group.
Two hydroxyl groups are protected as triethylsilyl (TES) ethers.

Alkylation of an in-situ formed enol ether with a propargyl mesylate. The ketone is converted to an enol ether, which then attacks the propargyl mesylate, displacing the mesylate group and forming a propargyl ether.

substeps.notes: Selective protection of one primary alcohol of but-2-yne-1,4-diol with TBDPS group.
Primary alcohol is oxidized to an aldehyde using Dess-Martin periodinane.
Rh-catalyzed Diels-Alder cycloaddition of an ynal with a silyloxydiene, followed by TMS deprotection and cyclization, forming an alpha,beta-unsaturated delta-lactone.
Stereoselective Luche reduction of an alpha,beta-unsaturated ketone to an allylic alcohol.
Silylation of a secondary alcohol using TBSCl to form a TBS ether, while a TBDPS ether remains untouched.
Epoxidation of the dihydropyran alkene using DMDO, forming a cis-epoxide with all stereocenters in the ring having the same relative configuration (dashed wedges).
Epoxide ring opening with 4-methoxybenzyl alcohol (PMBOH) catalyzed by zinc chloride, forming a PMB ether and a free hydroxyl group. Yield reported over 2 steps.
Oxidation of a secondary alcohol to a ketone.
Allylmagnesium bromide adds to the ketone, forming a tertiary alcohol with new stereochemistry. Existing stereocenters and protecting groups remain unchanged.
O-alkylation of a secondary alcohol to form a benzyl ether. The protecting groups (TBS, TBDPS, PMB) remain untouched.
Selective deprotection of p-methoxybenzyl (PMB) ether to a hydroxyl group using trifluoroacetic acid (TFA). The anomeric carbon's stereochemistry becomes unspecified (wavy bond).
Ozonolysis of the terminal alkene to an aldehyde, followed by intramolecular cyclization of the aldehyde with the existing hemiacetal hydroxyl group to form a fused bicyclic acetal/hemiacetal system.
Methylation of the anomeric alcohol to form a methyl glycoside.
Deprotection of TBDPS and TBS protecting groups to hydroxyl groups using tetrabutylammonium fluoride.
Protection of the terminal primary propargyl alcohol with tert-butyldiphenylsilyl chloride (TBDPSCl).
O-alkylation of a secondary alcohol to form a PMB ether.
Deprotection of a TBDPS-protected propargyl alcohol using tetrabutylammonium fluoride (TBAF). The silyl ether is converted to a free alcohol.
Mesylation of a primary alcohol to form a mesylate ester.

sequence.notes: Deprotection of two triethylsilyl (TES) ethers to hydroxyl groups using tetrabutylammonium fluoride (TBAF).
Intramolecular cyclization/rearrangement involving the alkyne and enol ether to form a spiro-lactone with an exocyclic methylene.
Selective protection of one hydroxyl group with a TBS group.
Oxidative deprotection of p-methoxybenzyl (PMB) ether to hydroxyl using DDQ.
Conversion of a secondary alcohol to a methyl dithiocarbonate.
Reductive removal of the S-methyl dithiocarbonate (xanthate) group and intramolecular cyclopropanation of the exocyclic alkene to form a new cyclopropane and fused ether ring.
Baeyer-Villiger oxidation of a ketone to a lactone using Magnesium monoperoxyphthalate (MMPP).
Deprotection of a TBS ether to a hydroxyl group.
Selective hydrogenolysis of a benzyl ether protecting group to a hydroxyl group on the sugar moiety.
Selective acetylation of a secondary hydroxyl group on the polycyclic core.
Acylation of a secondary alcohol using an acid chloride and a base.
Stereoselective reduction of a ketone to an alcohol.
Debenzylation of a complex polycyclic structure, specifically converting a benzyl ether to a hydroxyl group.

Substitution of the anomeric OMe group of the sugar moiety with a phenylseleno (PhSe) group. The product is shown with a wavy bond at the anomeric carbon, indicating mixed or unspecified stereochemistry. The corrected SMILES for the product retains the stereochemistry (alpha) consistent with the Azadirachtin A core structure, but the wavy bond nuance is noted.
Oxidation of an alpha-hydroxyl selenide to a gem-diol through selenoxide elimination and subsequent hydration. The SePh group is replaced by a new hydroxyl group with defined stereochemistry.
